            "id": "electric-circuits-current",
            "title": "Electric Circuits and Current",
            "text": "**Electric current** is the flow of electric charge, measured in amperes (A). **Voltage** (V) is electrical pressure that drives current, while **resistance** (R) opposes current flow. **Ohm's Law** states that V = IR, where current is directly proportional to voltage and inversely proportional to resistance.\n\n**Series circuits** have components connected end-to-end, sharing the same current but dividing voltage. **Parallel circuits** have components connected across the same voltage source, dividing current but sharing voltage. **Electrical power** is calculated as P = VI = I²R = V²/R, measured in watts (W).\n\nIn Ghana, understanding circuits is essential for **safe house wiring**. Proper circuit design prevents overloads, uses appropriate wire sizes, and includes safety devices like circuit breakers and fuses. Electricians must understand voltage drops, power calculations, and safety regulations.",
