            "id": "magnetism-electromagnetic-induction",
            "title": "Magnetism and Electromagnetic Induction",
            "text": "**Magnetic fields** are regions where magnetic forces act. They are represented by field lines that show direction and strength. **Magnetic flux** (Φ) measures the number of field lines passing through an area, measured in webers (Wb).\n\n**Faraday's Law** states that induced electromotive force (emf) equals the rate of change of magnetic flux: ε = -N(ΔΦ/Δt), where N is the number of turns. **Lenz's Law** states that induced current creates a magnetic field that opposes the change causing it.\n\n**Generators** convert mechanical energy to electrical energy through electromagnetic induction. In Ghana, **Bui Dam** uses this principle—falling water spins turbines connected to coils in magnetic fields, generating electricity for the national grid.",
